  "prompt": "Who is the inventor of calculator?",
  "response": "The invention of the calculator does not credit a single individual but rather spans a series of developments by various pioneers over time. \n\nThe early mechanical calculator known as the \"Pascaline\" was invented by Blaise Pascal in 1642. Later, German polymath Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz improved upon Pascal's design and developed the \"Stepped Reckoner\" in 1673, which could perform multiplication and division.\n\nIn the 19th century, Charles Babbage conceptualized the idea of a more complex analytical engine, which could be considered a precursor to the modern computer and calculator.\n\nElectronic calculators as we know them started to emerge in the mid-20th century, and many inventors and engineers contributed to their development, including advancements by the Bell Punch Company, Texas Instruments, and Casio.\n\nThus, the calculator is the result of cumulative improvements over centuries by different inventors.",
